│ "thoughts": "### 1. Understanding the Issue\n\nThe           │
│ `slp-vectorizer` is crashing with an assertion failure,      │
│ `OpIdx < Operands.size()`, inside                            │
│ `BoUpSLP::TreeEntry::getOperand`. This indicates that we are │
│ trying to access an operand of a `TreeEntry` with an         │
│ out-of-bounds index. A `TreeEntry` represents a bundle of    │
│ scalar instructions that are candidates for vectorization.   │
│ Its `Operands` list stores pointers to other `TreeEntry`s    │
│ that produce its inputs. An out-of-bounds access here means  │
│ there's a mismatch between the number of operands an         │
│ instruction has and the number of operand entries we've      │
│ created for it in our vectorization tree.\n\n### 2.          │
│ Analyzing `opt`'s Log and Backtrace\n\nThe backtrace points  │
│ to the cost calculation phase, specifically within           │
│ `getEntryCost`, which is called from `getTreeCost` during a  │
│ horizontal reduction analysis                                │
│ (`HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce`). This tells us the      │
│ vectorizer is evaluating the profitability of vectorizing a  │
│ horizontal reduction pattern.\n\nThe `opt` log shows the     │
│ vectorizer building a large tree of dependencies. The crash  │
│ occurs right after it prints the cost calculation for `Tree: │
│ 19`, which is a bundle of `trunc` instructions.\n\n```\nSLP: │
│ Calculated costs for Tree:\n19.\nOperand 0:\n    %conv73i =  │
│ xor i64 0, 0\n    ...\nScalars:\n    %2 = trunc i64 %conv73i │
│ to i16\n    ...\nState: Vectorize\n...\nUserTreeIndices:     │
│ {User:17 EdgeIdx:1},\n...\nSLP: Adding cost 0 for bundle     │
│ Idx: 19, n=4 [  %2 = trunc i64 %conv73i to i16,              │
│ ..].\n```\n\nThe `trunc` instruction is a cast and has only  │
│ one operand. The log correctly shows `Operand 0`. The        │
│ problem must lie in how the user of this `TreeEntry` (the    │
│ parent in the dependency graph) is processed. The            │
│ `UserTreeIndices` field tells us that `TreeEntry` 19 is used │
│ by `TreeEntry` 17 at its operand index 1.\n\n### 3. Root     │
│ Cause Analysis\n\nLet's investigate the state at the time of │
│ the crash using the debugger.\n\nThe crash occurs inside a   │
│ lambda within `getEntryCost`. This lambda is responsible for │
│ calculating the cost of gathering the operands for the       │
│ current `TreeEntry`. It iterates through the operands and,   │
│ if an operand is not a simple broadcast or constant, it      │
│ recursively calls `getEntryCost` on the operand's            │
│ `TreeEntry`.\n\nThe key is the `UserTreeIndices` set. When a │
│ `TreeEntry` is created, it registers itself as a user of its │
│ operand `TreeEntry`s. This registration includes the operand │
│ index. For example, for `z = add x, y`, the `TreeEntry` for  │
│ `z` has two operands. It registers itself as a user of `x`'s │
│ `TreeEntry` at index 0 and `y`'s `TreeEntry` at index        │
│ 1.\n\nIn our case, the `trunc` instructions in `TreeEntry`   │
│ 19 have only one operand. However, when `TreeEntry` 17 (a    │
│ bundle of `or` instructions) was created, it seems to have   │
│ incorrectly registered itself as a user of `TreeEntry` 19 at │
│ `EdgeIdx:1`.\n\n```\nSLP: Calculated costs for               │
│ Tree:\n17.\n...\nOperand 1:\n    %2 = trunc i64 %conv73i to  │
│ i16\n    ...\nUserTreeIndices: {User:0                       │
│ EdgeIdx:2},\n```\n\nThe `or` instructions in `TreeEntry` 17  │
│ (like `%3 = or i16 0, %2`) have two operands. The first is a │
│ constant `0`, and the second comes from the `trunc`          │
│ instructions in `TreeEntry` 19. The `trunc` instructions     │
│ should be operand 1.\n\nThe issue arises from a subtle bug   │
│ in how `TreeEntry`s are reused. The vectorizer tries to      │
│ reuse existing `TreeEntry`s to avoid re-computation. The log │
│ shows:\n\n```\nSLP:  reset schedule because   %3 = or i16 0, │
│ %2 was already scheduled\n...\nSLP: try schedule bundle [    │
│ %3 = or i16 0, %2; ...\n```\n\nThis indicates that           │
│ `TreeEntry`s are being created, then potentially discarded   │
│ and recreated. During this process, it appears the           │
│ `UserTreeIndices` are not being correctly cleared or         │
│ updated. A `TreeEntry` that was previously a user at index 2 │
│ (`EdgeIdx:2`) might be reused for a different instruction    │
│ bundle where it should be a user at a different              │
│ index.\n\nSpecifically, when `BoUpSLP::buildTree` is called, │
│ it might reuse a previously allocated but invalidated        │
│ `TreeEntry`. If this entry still contains stale              │
│ `UserTreeIndices` from its previous life, the cost model     │
│ will later try to access operands using incorrect indices,   │
│ leading to the crash.\n\nThe fix is to ensure that when a    │
│ `TreeEntry` is initialized or reused, its `UserTreeIndices`  │
│ set is cleared. This prevents stale user information from a  │
│ previous vectorization attempt from corrupting the analysis  │
│ of a new one.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix is │
│ to add `UserTreeIndices.clear()` at the beginning of the     │
│ `BoUpSLP::TreeEntry` constructor. This ensures that whenever │
│ a `TreeEntry` object is created (or reused via placement     │
│ new), it starts with a clean slate regarding its             │
│ users.\n\n```cpp\nFile:                                      │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp\nLines:      │
│ 3159-3162\nTreeEntry(const BoUpSLP &R)\n    : TheSLP(R),     │
│ State(NeedToCompute), VectorizedValue(nullptr),\n            │
│ ReuseShuffleIndices(R.getVF(), -1) {\n                       │
│ UserTreeIndices.clear();\n}\n```\n\n### 5. Conclusion\n\nThe │
│ root cause of the assertion failure is stale user            │
│ information (`UserTreeIndices`) in reused `TreeEntry`        │
│ objects. The complex and redundant structure of the input IR │
│ leads the SLP vectorizer to attempt and then reset its       │
│ scheduling, causing `TreeEntry` objects to be                │
│ re-initialized. Without explicitly clearing the              │
│ `UserTreeIndices`, old parent-child relationships persist    │
│ incorrectly, leading the cost model to access a non-existent │
│ operand. By clearing this set in the `TreeEntry`             │
│ constructor, we guarantee that each new vectorization        │
│ candidate starts with a correct and empty set of users,      │
│ resolving the crash."})                                      │
